>You must have a fire-detection and warning system. You may need different types of detectors, depending on the type of building and work carried out in the building.</p>\n\n<h2>Fire fighting equipment</h2>\n\n<p>The types of equipment you need depend on your business premises. You may need different types of fire fighting equipment. If the fire fighting equipment is not automatic, eg a fire extinguisher, you&rsquo;ll need to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have them properly installed, tested and maintained  </li>\n  <li>train your staff to use them</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Maintenance and testing</h3>\n\n<p>You must carry out regular checks to make sure that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>all fire alarm systems are working  </li>\n  <li>the emergency lighting is working </li>\n  <li>you record any faults in systems and equipment </li>\n  <li>all escape routes are clear and the floor is in a good state  </li>\n  <li>all fire escapes can be opened easily</li>\n  <li>automatic fire doors close correctly  </li>\n  <li>fire exit signs are in the right place  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’re responsible if your fire safety equipment fails due to poor maintenance - if there’s a maintenance contract in place, the contractor is responsible.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Fire drills and training</h2>\n\n<p>You need to train new staff when they start work and tell all employees about any new fire risks.</p>\n\n<p>You should carry out at least 1 fire drill per year and record the results. The results should be kept as part of your fire safety and evacuation plan. The drills must be carried out during working hours and include all staff.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/enforcement-appeals-and-penalties","slug":"enforcement-appeals-and-penalties","order":6,"title":"Enforcement, appeals and penalties","body":"<p>Your local fire and rescue authority can send a fire safety officer to inspect your premises to check it complies with fire safety regulations.</p>\n\n<p>They might issue an informal notice suggesting changes you should consider making to make your premises safer.</p>\n\n<p>They could also give you one of several different formal fire safety notices. The fire and rescue authority will tell you what you need to do to fix the problems given in the notice.</p>\n\n<h2>Alterations notice</h2>\n\n<p>You could get an alterations notice if your premises has high safety risks or will have high safety risks if the use of the premises changes.</p>\n\n<h2>Enforcement notice</h2>\n\n<p>You could get an enforcement notice if the fire and rescue authority thinks you haven&rsquo;t followed fire safety regulations.</p>\n\n<h2>Prohibition notice</h2>\n\n<p>These take effect immediately if the fire and rescue authority thinks that the fire risk is so great that access to your premises needs to be prohibited or restricted.</p>\n\n<h2>Appeals</h2>\n\n<p>If you disagree with the decision to issue a fire safety notice you may be able to arrange an informal review from your fire and rescue authority.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;ve already got the notice, you can appeal to your local magistrates’ court within 21 days. </p>\n\n<p>In certain circumstances, you and the fire and rescue authority can ask for a &lsquo;determination&rsquo; from the Communities Secretary to solve a dispute.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/15113/1497577.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Guidance on the determination process' (PDF, 158KB)\">Download ‘Guidance on the determination process’ (PDF, 158KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Penalties</h2>\n\n<p>You can be prosecuted for not following fire safety regulations. If you&rsquo;re convicted you could get a fine or go to prison.</p>\n\n<p>Minor penalties can be up to £5,000. Major penalties can have unlimited fines and up to 2 years in prison.</p>\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"Business premises and business rates","id"